Recommended Next Steps

Build document classes first. Implement TurnOfTheCenturyActor and TurnOfTheCenturyItem in module/documents.mjs, then register them in turn-of-the-century.mjs. This is where we should calculate ability modifiers, skill totals, armor class, encumbrance, equipped weapon state, passive senses, and derived movement.

Create a small rules engine for modifiers. Normalize quirk effects, item effects, consumable effects, and condition/effect impacts into one shared modifier format. Then actor preparation can aggregate them into final attributes. This will prevent every item type from needing custom one-off math.

Add basic sheets. Start with one actor sheet and one generic item sheet that can render/edit all current data. They do not need to be beautiful yet; they need to make the system usable and expose all fields safely.

Implement core rolls. Add ability checks, saving throws, skill checks, attack rolls, damage rolls, healing rolls, and sanity checks. Once rolls exist, weapons, consumables, and effects become testable.

Implement inventory and equipment behavior. Add methods like equipItem, unequipItem, moveToPack, readyWeapon, consumeAmmunition, and applyArmorClass. This is central to your slot-based design.

Add seed compendiums. Create a minimal playable set: 6-10 weapons, 6 armor pieces, 8 consumables, 8 quirks, 6 professions, 8 ethnicities, 10 effects, and 3 actors. This will reveal model weaknesses faster than more abstract schema work.

Add migrations and versioning discipline. Before much content exists, add a migration scaffold keyed to system version. That will save pain as field names change.

Improve manifest polish. Add folder-backed packs if you intend to ship compendium content, add compatibility updates for your target Foundry version, and fill localization strings.